ipt to handle the WORKDIR conflict by adjusting mount paths\n   - **Option B**: Modify the Dockerfile to be compatible with local checkouts\n   - **Option C**: Disable the local checkout feature for this build\n   - **Option D**: Adjust the build command to not use local checkout when WORKDIR is set to `/src`\n\n3. **Build Context**: The Docker build succeeded, meaning the Dockerfile itself is valid. The issue is in the post-build fuzzing setup phase where the build system tries to use the built image with local source code.\n\n4. **Original Error Context**: The original build error (from the historical log) was a linker error with `libz.a` file format. The current error represents a regression - we\'ve gone from a compilation/linking error to a configuration/scripting error. This suggests the build system setup introduced a new problem.\n\n**Recommended Approach**:\n1. First fix the configuration error about local checkout vs WORKDIR\n2. Then address the original linker error with `libz.a`\n3. Ensure the fix doesn\'t break the Docker build process\n\n**Key Files to Examine**:\n1. `/root/fix_build_agent/oss-fuzz/projects/binutils/Dockerfile` - Check for `WORKDIR /src` directive\n2. `/root/fix_build_agent/oss-fuzz/projects/binutils/build.sh` - Check build script logic\n3. `/root/fix_build_agent/oss-fuzz/infra/helper.py` - Check local checkout handling logic\n4. Any configuration files in the project config directory that might affect build behavior\n\n--- 【LESSONS FROM PREVIOUS ATTEMPTS】 ---\n- [Attempt 318] Identical linker error persists from attempt 316. The zlib library format remains incompatible with AFL++ Clang toolchain. Despite previous attempts to rebuild zlib, the issue persists unchanged. This indicates the current approach of trying to fix zlib build within the existing build process is not working. Need to fundamentally re-evaluate how zlib is being built or sourced in the binutils-gdb project.\n- [Attempt 1] First build attempt failed with linker error